<subsection xml:id="subsec-fractional-indices" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Fractional indices</title>
    <p>
        
    </p>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                Investigate what happens when a number is raised to a fractional exponent.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Instructions</alert>
            </p>
           
            <p>
               <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                         Consider the number <m>25^\frac{1}{2}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="i)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Express it as a product of its prime factors in index form .
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Apply the law of indices to simplify the above expression.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Work out the following: 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="a)" cols="3">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           <m>8^\frac{2}{3}</m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>81^\frac{3}{4}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>27^\frac{1}{3}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Discuss your work with your fellow learners.
                    </p>
                </li>
               </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <definition xml:id="def-fractional-indices">
        <statement>
            <p>
                 Fractional indices, also known as rational indices, are used to represent roots of numbers in index form. 
        
            </p>
            <p>
                 A fractional index indicates that the base is raised to a power and then the root is taken.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
        <alert>Key Takeaway</alert>
    </p>
    <p>
        Given a base <m>a</m> and a fractional index <m>\frac{m}{n}</m>, it can be expressed as:
        <me>a^{\frac{m}{n}} = \sqrt[n]{a^m}</me>
    </p>
    <p>
        This means that we first raise <m>a</m> to the power of <m>m</m> and then take the <m>n</m>-th root of the result.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
              Evaluate:  
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>16^\frac{3}{4}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>4^{-\frac{1}{2}}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            First, express  <m>16^{\frac{3}{4}}</m> as a product of its prime factors: 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore,
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>16^{\frac{3}{4}} = \amp (4^2)^\frac{3}{4}</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 4^{2 \times \frac{3}{4}}</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 4^ \frac{3}{2}</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp (\sqrt{4})^3</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 2^3</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Expressing <m>4^{-\frac{1}{2}}</m> as a product of its prime factors we have:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>4^{-\frac{1}{2}} = \amp (2^2)^{-\frac{1}{2}}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 2^{2 \times (-\frac{1}{2})}</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 2^{-1}</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{2}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
    
</subsection>